Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 400 degrees. Bring a large #pot of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve @bell pepper{1}; remove stem and seeds. Cut @tomato{1} into six wedges. Peel and thinly slice @garlic{1%clove}. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

Place bell pepper and tomato on a #baking sheet{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{1%tsp} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Arrange bell pepper cut sides down.

Roast on middle rack until veggies are softened and lightly charred, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Let bell pepper cool slightly, then transfer to a #cutting board{} and thinly slice into strips.

> While veggies roast, heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add sausage or turkey and season with salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, 4-6 minutes. Turn off heat; transfer to a plate. Wipe out pan.

When veggies are almost done, gently add @spinach and ricotta ravioli{9%ounce} to pot of boiling water. Reduce to a simmer and cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente and floating to the top, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water (1 cup for 4 servings), then drain.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium heat. Add garlic and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> Use pan used for sausage or turkey here.

Add @veggie stock concentrate{1}, @cream cheese{2%tbsp}, @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, half the @parmesan cheese{3%tbsp} (save the rest for serving), ¼ cup reserved pasta cooking water (½ cup for 4 servings), and @butter{1%tbsp} to pan with garlic.

Whisk until combined and creamy, then stir in roasted tomato and sliced bell pepper.

Add a squeeze of lemon juice to taste. Season generously with salt and pepper.

> Stir sausage or turkey into sauce until combined.

Add @cooking oil{2%tsp} to large pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground turkey{10%ounce} and season with salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}.

Add drained ravioli to pan with sauce; gently toss until thoroughly coated.

> TIP: If necessary, stir in more pasta cooking water a splash at a time until ravioli are coated in a creamy sauce.

Divide between plates and top with remaining Parmesan and lemon zest to taste. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.